{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e7d4484-cb3a-4325-a630-c1785fd97064","content":"The template is **close but not fully ready** for NuGet publishing. Here's what I found:\n\n**Required/Critical:**\n- ✅ `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `tags` — all present\n- ⚠️ **`Framework` symbol is missing `replaces`** — the parameter won't substitute anything in project files (e.g., the `<TargetFramework>` in `.csproj`). Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` so the chosen framework actually gets applied.\n\n**Recommended for NuGet:**\n- ⚠️ Missing **`$schema`** (`\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"`) — enables editor validation.\n- ⚠️ Missing **`groupIdentity`** — needed to group related templates and handle updates cleanly via NuGet.\n- ⚠️ Missing **`preferNameDirectory`** — typically `true` for project templates.\n\n**Summary:** The `Framework` symbol without `replaces` is the most impactful issue — users could pick a framework and it would silently do nothing. The missing `groupIdentity` can also cause problems when updating the package. Would you like me to fix these?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3e788083-88f5-4f31-abda-ed809eb28239","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and editor support. Should be `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packaging so templates can be grouped (e.g., different language versions of the same template).\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template are installed.\n\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — A nice-to-have that improves user experience.\n5. **The `Framework` symbol's `choices` format looks valid** — The object format works in newer template engine versions, though I should double-check that the `defaultValue` of `\"net9.0\"` matches one of the available choices.\n6. **The `replaces` property is missing from the `Framework` symbol definition** — This is needed to specify what text in the template files should be replaced with the selected framework value.\n\nLooking at the required metadata fields, most are present: `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `classifications`, and the language/type tags are all there. The main gaps for NuGet publishing are the missing `$schema` at the top level and that `replaces` property on the Framework symbol.","outputTokens":937,"requestId":"280B:24244F:F457CE:1345A5C:69FFD938"},"id":"30f5c7f5-69a6-4501-8244-248fcd5ec380","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:03:10.696Z","parentId":"64745f1a-2232-4fed-a578-cca51e08bff3"}
